          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":60,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"24 km easy long run at 5:04–5:34/km. Keep effort conversational throughout — this is your aerobic foundation, not a race. Hydrate and fuel every 45 min.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Sleep and nutrition are doing the work today — this is where adaptation happens.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Optional 30–45 min low-impact cross-training (cycling, swimming, yoga). Keep heart rate easy. This supports aerobic base without adding run stress.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"12 km total: 3 km warm-up at easy pace, 6 km at threshold pace (4:12/km), 3 km cool-down. Threshold work builds your lactate clearance — the engine behind your marathon pace.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Let Thursday's tempo work absorb. Quality over quantity — recovery is part of the training.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"notes\":\"14 km total: 3 km warm-up, 6×1 km at interval pace (3:54/km) with 400 m jog recovery, 2 km cool-down. Intervals lift your VO2max ceiling, which ultimately raises your marathon pace ceiling too.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"10 km easy at 5:04–5:34/km. This is your recovery run — resist the urge to push. Running easy on tired legs is a skill, and it matters.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to Week 1, Priya — and what a strong foundation you're bringing into this block. Your recent half-marathon PB of 1:32 and consistent 60 km weeks show you're ready to take on marathon-specific training. This first week mirrors your recent training load (60 km) to let you settle into the plan's rhythm without a shock to the system. The structure — long run Sunday, tempo Thursday, intervals Friday, easy Saturday — is designed to fit your 4-day schedule and post-7 AM start requirement. Every run has a physiological purpose: the long run builds aerobic endurance, the tempo sharpens lactate threshold, the intervals raise your VO2max ceiling, and the easy run aids recovery while maintaining volume. Your target of 3:15 (4:37/km marathon pace) is ambitious but well within reach given your VDOT of 49.7 — a sub-3:15 is a natural next step from your half-marathon fitness. What questions do you have before we get started?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
